        <div class="col-lg-12">
          <strong>Claim: </strong>Bermuda will not get a fair deal unless the airport project goes out to tender.
          <br>
          <p><strong>The Truth:</strong>
          The Bermuda Government has used the tender process for years on its large building projects, and has seen cost overruns totaling hundreds of millions of dollars. More and more, other countries are finding the same thing– asking for tenders, especially with big infrastructural projects, almost always results in cost overruns. That’s why many governments are finding public-private partnerships a better way to cost-effectively finance large infrastructure projects like airports. The arrangement we have made with the Canadian Commercial Corporation is a type of public-private partnership that involves no upfront spending for the airport by Bermuda, and no new debt for Bermuda. We are also given a guarantee by the Canadian Government that their project will be delivered on time, on budget, and according to specifications. That’s a huge plus for Bermuda’s taxpayers since it means there won’t be cost overruns – period.</p>
